Not sure of how to bring this issue to attention generally, so tagging two of the possibly active core devs.

@jonahwilliams @stuartmorgan could you add tags "found in release 3.10" and possibly UP the priority of this issue?

It might not be obvious on first sight, but this is crucial issue. In many localizations (including my national) essential letters of the language can be typed only by this method (typing accent + letter afterwards) and no other way. Many of Flutter apps users use eg. iPad with the external keyboard to input the texts comfortably. While having this issue this make  typing text into Flutter app not possible in many countries (aka localizations) including mine. From my understanding there is "some" implementation of typing accented letters in Flutter. It is just buggy and doesnt work. So fixing this issue should possibly not be reinventing the wheel. I am coming from the notion that when I press accent key, it appears inside input field with underscore as if it was expecting the following letter for accenting. However after pressing the following letter the underscore gets away and the letter is just put next to the accent. In best case it might be just issue of some missing localized keymaps of accented letters in the Flutter core. Please, lets not get this issue unnoticed. We are making text data intensive Flutter app for several thousands of enterprise clients and currently they just cant type in text in our national language using external keyboard. Thanks for any reaction.

So, update on our end, we ended up taking the route of a custom `TextEditingController`, along with a generated inline database of accented characters to correct:

```dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';
import 'package:loggable/loggable.dart';

part '_accented_characters.dart';

class AccentedCharsTextEditingController extends TextEditingController
    with Loggable {
  AccentedCharsTextEditingController({super.text});

  AccentedCharsTextEditingController.fromValue(super.value) : super.fromValue();

  @override
  set value(TextEditingValue value) {
    final baseOffset = value.selection.baseOffset;
    final extentOffset = value.selection.extentOffset;
    try {
      if (value.text.isNotEmpty && baseOffset >= 2) {
        if (baseOffset == extentOffset) {
          final prefix = value.text[baseOffset - 2];
          final char = value.text[baseOffset - 1];
          final accentedChar = accentedChars[prefix];

          if (accentedChar?.containsKey(char) ?? false) {
            value = TextEditingValue(
              text: value.text.replaceRange(
                baseOffset - 2,
                baseOffset,
                accentedChar![char]!,
              ),
              selection: TextSelection.collapsed(offset: baseOffset - 1),
            );
          }
        }
      }
    } on ArgumentError catch (err, st) {
      logWarning(
        'Error when setting value in AccentedCharsTextEditingController',
        error: err,
        stackTrace: st,
      );
    }
    super.value = value;
  }

  @override
  List<String> get loggers => ['ui.AccentedCharsTextEditingController'];
}
```

And in '_accented_characters.dart, we have a very large structure like this:

```dart
part of 'accented_text_editing_controller.dart';

const accentedChars = {
  '`': {
    '`': '`',
    'à': 'à',
    'À': 'À',
    ...
  },
  '^': {
    '^': '^',
    'â': 'â',
    'Â': 'Â',
    'ê': 'ê',
    ...
  },
  ...
}
```

It's not ideal, but with AI, the database is pretty easy to populate, and we haven't had an issue with this since then. Hope this helps some folks out there!

But it's a hack. The true fix should be done in Flutter.

